The beachcomber-pilot looked up. Recognizing the Hardys, he did not hesitate. Before the fleeing Chameleon knew what was happening, he had been tripped and thrown face down to the sand. By the time Frank and Joe reached him, Clams was seated astride the doctor's shoulders, thwarting the man's efforts to rise. When Mont-rose saw the Hardys, he ceased to struggle and the beachcomber let him get up.\par
"Now s'pose you fellows tell me what this is all about," Clams demanded.\par
The boys gave him an account of everything they knew, including the prime clue of the cuff links.\par
Clams frowned and said, "If we search this jerk, mebbe we can find out more."\par
Montrose objected, but Frank and Joe held him as the beachcomber began going through the man's pockets. As he looked over the contents of the doctor's wallet, Clams exclaimed:\par
"Quite a bunch o' dough. Hm. A hundred-\par
